Part2¶

This section of the project is a report about the employees. This report summarizes the total revenue each employee generates, how many products they sell, what products they are able to sell, their sales performance across years and how they do in different regions. Using various statistics and graphs/tables, we will explore what drives their performance and suggestions on how performance can be improved. At the very end, there is a summary of the strength and weakness of each employee.

A SQL query is used to join different tables together and is then converted into a pandas dataframe for analysis

In [17]:
# Create Query Used for Analysis
query1 = """
    SELECT e.EmployeeID, o.OrderID, e.LastName, e.FirstName, e.Title, od.UnitPrice, od.Quantity, od.Discount, p.ProductName, o.OrderDate, ((od.UnitPrice-od.Discount)*od.Quantity) as 'TotalSold', o.ShipCountry, c.CategoryName
    FROM 'Orders' as o
    INNER JOIN 'Order Details' as od ON o.OrderID = od.OrderID
    INNER JOIN 'Products' as p ON od.ProductID = p.ProductID
    INNER JOIN 'Categories' as c ON p.CategoryID = c.CategoryID
    INNER JOIN 'Employees' as e ON o.EmployeeID = e.EmployeeID
    """
emp = pd.read_sql(query1, con)
emp

The created dataset is cleaned to make analysis easier such as changing the order date to only show the year, combining the first and last name of an employee together, and changing categorical variable into a category type.

In [18]:
# Clean Dataset
emp['OrderDate'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(emp['OrderDate']).year
emp['EmployeeName'] = emp["FirstName"] + " " + emp["LastName"]
emp[["Title","LastName","EmployeeID","OrderID","FirstName","ProductName","OrderDate"]] = emp[["Title","LastName","EmployeeID","OrderID","FirstName","ProductName","OrderDate"]].apply(lambda x: x.astype("category"))
emp

#Allows iteration of employees
def sort_data(i):
    #Sorts data to only the specific employee's
    currEmp = emp[(emp["EmployeeID"] == i)]
    
    return currEmp

For part 3, We are going to use pandas-on-spark Data Frame to view different variable means across season from the NFL dataset. Using pandas-on-spark will make things easier than the method that was used in HW4. After finding the mean and standard deviation for the Quarter variable, we will convert the pandas-on-spark dataframe back to a normal pandas data frame and plot the data.

psdf = ps.from_pandas(pdf)

Use for loop to specify which variable in the data is needed to view, and extract the information of these three variables and append each of them into three different lists

In [88]:
Mean = []
Std = []
Name = []
for i in list(psdf.columns):
    if i in ['AQ1','AQ2','AQ3','AQ4','AFinal','HQ1','HQ2','HQ3','HQ4','HFinal']:
        Mean.append(psdf[i].mean())
        Std.append(psdf[i].std())
        Name.append(str(i))
    else:
        continue

Zip the three list into one Data frame for future usage
